\begin_layout Standard
Grammatical Evolution procedure can be considered as a genetic algorithm,
 where the chromosomes are sets of randomly chosen integers.
 These integers represent production rules of the provided BNF grammar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bnf1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 BNF grammars are usually expressed as sets having the form 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $G=\left(N,T,S,P\right)$
\end_inset


\series default
,
 where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The set
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 
\series default
contains the non-terminal symbols of the grammar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The set 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 
\series default
includes the terminal symbols of the grammar.

\series bold
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 denotes the start symbol of the grammar,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the set of production rules of the grammar.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Grammatical Evolution procedure utilizes an extended version of the initial BNF grammar by adding enumeration in the the production rules.
 As an example of an extended BNF grammar consider the grammar shown in
\series bold
 
\series default
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BNF-grammar-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.

\series bold
 
\series default
The notation < > is used to enclose the non - terminal symbols of the grammar.
 The value 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 denotes the dimension of the input data.
 The Grammatical Evolution procedure starts from the start symbol of the program and gradually it creates valid programs in the underlying language,
 using the production rules of the grammar.
 The general scheme of the production procedure has as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Get
\series default
 the next element V from the chromosome that is under processing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Select
\series default
 the next rule using the equation Rule = V mod NR.
 The symbol NR denotes the number of production rules for the under processing non – terminal symbol.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A full working example of the production procedure is the chromosome 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\left[9,8,6,4,16,10,17,23,8,14\right]
\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d=3$
\end_inset

.
 After a series of steps,
 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x_{2}+\cos\left(x_{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 is produced for the grammar of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BNF-grammar-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The production steps are shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:table_with_steps"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An example of an extended BNF grammar.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:BNF-grammar-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

