\begin_layout Subsection
The feature construction method
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-feature-construction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The technique of feature construction produces artificial features for classification or regression problems as non - linear transformations of the original ones.
 The new features are evaluated using a machine learning technique,
 such as artificial neural networks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nn1,nn2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or a Radial Basis Function (RBF) networks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rbf1,rbf2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This method was presented initially in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fc1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Also,
 this method was used in many areas,
 such as Spam Identification 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fc2"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
 Fetal heart classification 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fc3"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,

\series bold
 
\series default
signal processing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fc4,fc5"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 etc.
 The process has the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Initialization
\series default
 step.
 
\series bold

\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Obtain 
\series default
the train data for the current problem.
 The train data have 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 pairs
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{i},t_{i}\right),\ i=1..M$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 The dimension of each vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.

\series default
 The values 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the expected outputs for each pattern.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Define 
\series default
the parameters of the genetic algorithm:
 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $N_{g}$
\end_inset


\series default
 stands for the the number of allowed generations,
 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
represents the number chromosomes,

\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
defines the selection rate and 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $p_{m}$
\end_inset


\series default
 the mutation rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Set
\series default
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{f}$
\end_inset

 the number of features that will construct the Grammatical Evolution procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Initialize
\series default
 the chromosomes in the population.
 Each chromosome is considered as a set of randomly chosen positive integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Set
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

,
 as the generation counter.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Genetic step
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
For 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,N_{c}$
\end_inset

 do
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Produce
\series default
 using the Grammatical Evolution procedure a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{f}$
\end_inset

 artificial features for the corresponding chromosome 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 These features are produced using the grammar of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BNF-grammar-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Transform
\series default
 the original dataset using the previously constructed features.
 The new training set is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{g_{i},j},t_{j}\right),\ j=1,..M$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Train 
\series default
a machine learning model denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 using the new training set.
 The fitness 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for the corresponding chromosome is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{M}\left(C\left(x_{g_{i},j}\right)-t_{j}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the proposed method the RBF network is used as the machine learning model,
 since the time required for its training is significantly lower than other models,
 such as neural networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Perform
\series default
 the selection procedure.
 During this procedure the chromosomes are firstly sorted according to their fitness values and the best
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-p_{s}\right)\times N_{C}$
\end_inset


\series default
 of them are copied intact to the next generation.

\series bold
 
\series default
The rest of the chromosomes will be substituted by new chromosomes produced during the procedures of crossover and mutation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Perform
\series default
 the crossover procedure.
 During this procedure 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}\times N_{c}$
\end_inset

 new chromosomes are produced.
 For every pair of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tilde{z},\tilde{w}\right)$
\end_inset

 of new chromosomes,
 two two distinct chromosomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z,w\right)$
\end_inset

 are selected from the current population.
 The selection is performed using the tournament selection.
 The new chromosomes are produced from the old ones using the one - point crossover procedure,
 which is graphically outlined in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:One-point-crossover"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
(OK)Perform
\series default
 the mutation procedure:
 for each each element of each chromosome,
 a random number 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 is selected.
 The underlying element is altered randomly when 
\begin_inset Formula $r\le p_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
EndFor
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Set
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=k+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
If
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $k\le N_{G}$
\end_inset

 goto 
\series bold
Genetic
\series default
 Step,
 else terminate the process and obtain the best chromosome 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}$
\end_inset

 with the lowest fitness value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Transform
\series default
 the corresponding test set,
 using the 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{f}$
\end_inset

 features obtained for chromosome 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Apply
\series default
 a machine learning model to the constructed test set and report the associated test error.
\series bold
.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename cross2.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One point crossover method,
 used in the Grammatical Evolution procedure.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:One-point-crossover"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
SmartGlove System and Sources of Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system of interest here as a primary data source is the SmartGlove system,
 a specially developed wearable system that has been created with the intent of telemonitoring motor symptoms of PD patients.
 It has been created with the support of the Operational Program of the Epirus Region 2014-2020 and ESPA 2014-2020 with a view of increasing innovative health and biotechnology solutions.
 The system of SmartGlove has three primary subsystems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Textile Glove:
 Made of durable,
 biocompatible materials,
 the glove has conductive areas on the palm and fingers that aid movement recognition.
 It is sweat-resistant and can be washed.
 It is also expected to last longer than 10 years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
System on Chip (SoC):
 The central processing unit encompasses a low-energy microcontroller that incorporates a Bluetooth 5.0 module,
 facilitating wireless data communication while utilizing minimal energy resources (with a typical operational range of 10-100 meters,
 contingent upon the surrounding environment).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sensors:
 The glove contains a multi-modal sensor suite:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Flex sensors to measure finger bending.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Contact sensors to detect finger-to-palm interaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 9-axis Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU),
 composed of a 3-axis accelerometer,
 3-axis gyroscope,
 and 3-axis magnetometer,
 to identify hands' orientation and movement.
 IMU has outputs of up to a sampling rate of 100 Hz and a resolution of 16 bits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system is supplemented with a power management circuitry developed for lithium-polymer batteries,
 as well as with flash memory used for transient storage of data.
 The SmartGlove complies with the IEC 60601-1 medical electrical apparatus safety standard,
 thus ensuring reliability for medical applications.
 The SmartGlove sends data via Bluetooth to the mobPark mobile app supporting Android 6.0+ as well as iOS 11+.
 The app acts as an intermediary providing the possibility of managing the profile of the users,
 providing screen-level cues of exercises,
 as well as capturing sensor data at a sampling rate of 100 Hz.
 Then the captured data gets securely sent via an encrypted HTTPS connection to a centralized cloud platform like AWS or Azure for storage,
 processing,
 and analyzing purposes with a consideration of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data Collection Exercises
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data recording was at a sampling rate of 100 Hz,
 selected to efficiently capture tremor frequencies from 4 to 6 Hz and also captures bradykinesia.
 Measurements were obtained before and after medication administration (i.e.,
 Levodopa) as a means of investigating therapeutic action.
 Four carefully designed motor tasks were incorporated into the experiment as described next:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exercise 1 (
\series bold
Postural Stability
\series default
):
 Patient sits with their hands resting on their legs with palms facing upwards and counts from 1 to 10.
 It checks postural stability and resting tremor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exercise 2 (
\series bold
Coordination
\series default
):
 The patient stands with their hands at shoulder height and counts to ten while attempting to touch their index fingers together.
 It is intended to assess tremor and coordination when standing for a long time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exercise 3 (
\series bold
Finger Tapping Speed
\series default
):
 With their palm flat,
 the participant taps their index finger back and forth against their thumb,
 then quickly returns to the starting position ten times.
 It is a traditional metric used to evaluate bradykinesia and motor speed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exercise 4 (
\series bold
Hand Speed of Closing and Opening
\series default
):
 For ten repetitions,
 the patient continuously makes a fist with an open palm and returns to an open position as quickly as they can.
 It checks for bradykinesia and hand rigidity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Feature extraction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerous features were taken from the raw sensor data (accelerometer,
 gyroscope,
 magnetometer) for each exercise in order to quantitatively describe the motor symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
 These features were computed using 50% overlap (50 samples,
 0.5 seconds) and sliding windows of 100 samples (1 second).
 These features extracted are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Statistical Properties:
 These characteristics provide a succinct explanation of the signal's variation and distribution.
 The following properties were calculated:
 Skewness,
 Kurtosis,
 Quartile Deviation,
 Mean,
 Standard Deviation,
 Variance,
 Minimum,
 Maximum,
 Range,
 Median,
 and Interquartile Range (IQR).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Energy Characteristics:
 These metrics assess the signal's intensity and degree of activity.
 Signal Magnitude Area (SMA),
 Root Mean Square (RMS),
 Total Energy,
 and Logarithmic Energy are among the features that were extracted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Frequency-Domain Features:
 These are essential for detecting tremors and take into account the signal's spectral characteristics.
 Included are the following features:
 Dominant Frequency,
 Spectral Flatness,
 Spectral Flux,
 Spectral Variability,
 Spectral Entropy,
 Spectral Centroid,
 Spectral Spread,
 and Spectral Roll-on(85%).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Dynamic and Nonlinear Features:
 These characteristics specify the signal's temporal fluctuations,
 complexity,
 and predictability.
 The following characteristics are taken into consideration:
 Mean Absolute Deviation (MAD),
 Root Mean Square of Successive Differences (RMSSD),
 Higuchi Fractal Dimension,
 Lyapunov Exponent,
 and Sample Entropy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since each feature includes specific aspects of motor impairment typical of the disease,
 such as tremor regularity,
 movement amplitude,
 and signal complexity,
 the selection of features was driven by a large body of literature on PD analysis.
 The characteristics for Movement Analysis in Parkinson's Disease are outlined in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Table-of-Characteristics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

